{{redirect|Bailii|Zygosaccharomyces bailii|Zygosaccharomyces bailii|the French king's administrative representative|Bailli}} {{EngvarB|date=December 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}} {{Infobox website | name = Bailii | logo = | logocaption = The logo of Bailii | screenshot = | collapsible = | caption = | url = {{URL|http://www.bailii.org|bailii.org}} | commercial = No | type = Legal database | registration = | language = | num_users = | content license = | owner = | author = | launch date = | alexa = | current status = }}
The '''British and Irish Legal Information Institute''' (BAILII, pronounced {{IPAc-en|b|eɪ|l|i:}} "Bailey") provides legal information, and especially reports of cases decided by courts, in the [[United Kingdom]] generally. Decisions from [[England and Wales]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], [[Northern Ireland]], [[Scotland]], the [[European Union]], and from the [[European Court of Human Rights]] are put online. It is a partial online database of British and Irish legislation, case law, law reform reports, treaties and some legal scholarship.<ref name="University of Strathclyde - Legal Research Skills - BAILII">{{cite web|url=http://ewds.strath.ac.uk/Blog/tabid/3585/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/98/British-and-Irish-Legal-Information-Institute--BAILII-Website-of-the-Week.aspx|title=British and Irish Legal Information Institute - BAILII - Website of the Week|publisher=[[University of Strathclyde]]|accessdate=24 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110621080240/http://ewds.strath.ac.uk/Blog/tabid/3585/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/98/British-and-Irish-Legal-Information-Institute--BAILII-Website-of-the-Week.aspx#|archive-date=21 June 2011|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="BAILII - About BAILII">{{cite web|url=http://www.bailii.org/bailii/|title= About BAILII|publisher=British and Irish Legal Information Institute|accessdate=24 February 2011}}</ref>
==Background== {{see also|Law report|Case citation}} Traditionally, legal information was accessible through a [[law report]], usually written by private individuals or groups. While court judgments have had official reports more recently, historically a court judgment would simply be spoken, and so publication of the precedents built up depended on their record by interested third parties. The [[Year Books]], which recorded judgments from 1268 to 1535, were probably compiled by law students. Other people, like the judge [[Sir Edward Coke]] from 1572 to 1615, then created their own series of reports. These would not necessarily be an accurate record of what was said. What was recorded might have been selective, or inaccurate. As the reporting industry developed, more people became involved and specialised in particular areas of law. The [[Incorporated Council of Law Reporting]] was created in 1885, and released copies of various cases. There still could be gaps in reporting however. With the advent of the Internet, it was possible to access multiple databases for a fee online, particularly [[Westlaw]] or [[LexisNexis|Lexis]]. However a freely available source had not yet been made.
BAILII was set up after a long and hard campaign by various activists including senior members of the Society for Computers & Law, such as then-Chairman Neil Cameron, barrister [[Laurie West-Knights QC]], Lord Saville and [[Henry Brooke (judge)|Lord Justice Brooke]], who were concerned about the lack of availability of court judgments to ordinary court users and were inspired by the [[Australasian Legal Information Institute]] (AustLII) LII.<ref>{{cite BAILII|litigants= Valedictory Address for Lord Justice Brooke |division=Civ| court=EWCA|year=2006|num=B1|date=2006-08-16}}(see ¶ 18)</ref> The aim was to provide free access to publicly available legal information.<ref name="University of Strathclyde - Legal Research Skills - BAILII"/> In 2006, BAILII included 5 [[jurisdiction]]s' fourteen databases.<ref name="University of Leicester - Library - BAILII">{{cite web|url=http://www.le.ac.uk/li/digital/BritishandIrishLegalInformationInstituteBAILII.html|title=BAILII (British and Irish Legal Information Institute)|publisher=[[University of Leicester]]|accessdate=24 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622061951/http://www.le.ac.uk/li/digital/BritishandIrishLegalInformationInstituteBAILII.html#|archive-date=22 June 2011|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The BAILII website is jointly hosted by the [[Institute of Advanced Legal Studies]], [[University of London]] and the [[University College Cork]]'s [[Law school]]<ref name="University of Strathclyde - Legal Research Skills - BAILII"/>
==Case citations== Bailii uses a "[[neutral citation]]" method, which was quickly adopted as a standard for citation of cases. The different series of cases that Bailii produces are as follows.
