== Criticism ==
BAILII has received criticisms due to the restrictions it imposes on its usage: in a ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' editorial, it was noted that BAILII had "done a wonderful job of making case law freely accessible to lawyers", including "historic and European data that is otherwise very difficult to find." However, it was also noted that as a small charity the service "struggles to afford to host its 297,000 judgments, and does not allow search engines to index them. In some instances it is not even clear whether the crown or the judge concerned holds the [[copyright]] to the words, and reproducing them on any other site is forbidden." <ref>{{cite web<!--|title=Guardian article discussing BAILII-->|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/sep/25/criminal-justice-uk-digital-database|title=Courts: judgement day|work=The Guardian|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref><!-- This is an editorial... -->
An organization known as Judgmental had been established to scrape information from BAILII and make it indexable by search engines. Founding members of Judgmental included [[Francis Irving]], one of the developers of [[TheyWorkForYou]].<ref name="judgemental-home-page">{{cite web|title=Judgemental Home Page|url=http://judgmental.org.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729164453/http://judgmental.org.uk/|archive-date=2016-07-29}}</ref> Judgmental shut down under threat of legal action regarding the court records for a libel case.<ref name="judgmental-libel-github">{{cite web|title=Historic judgmental page on github |url=https://github.com/frabcus/judgmental/blob/da575486c39821d00c11662e56e89d83660810a7/public_html/brb.html}}</ref> {{better source|date=September 2016}}
Former BAILII chairman [[Henry Brooke (judge)|Henry Brooke]] defended criticisms, stating that the restrictions on indexing were to ensure that records could be retroactively edited or removed for clerical or legal reasons, such as errors, information that was not authorized to be published, or records that have not been properly anonymized. Brooke went on to explain that BAILII "[does] not consider that taking the extra step of making the judgments searchable, using Google or other search engines, is necessary in order to achieve the primary objective of making judgments of the courts freely available to the public." He also stated that the restriction on redistribution was to protect its "value-added content", such as "converting it into a suitable format and making efforts to prevent the publication of material that must not be published."<ref name="scl-judgementday">{{cite web|title=Judgment Day for BAILII|url=http://www.scl.org/site.aspx?i=ed22972|publisher=SCL - The IT Law Community|accessdate=14 September 2016}}</ref>
== Access to case law ==
Much of the material available on BAILII is duplicated elsewhere, for example legislation and rulings of some courts (such as the Supreme Court). BAILII has an agreement with the Ministry of Justice indemnifying it from some legal prosecutions.<ref name="scl-judgementday"/> BAILII has historically received payment as part of this contract. In the 2010/2011 tax year BAILII received {{Currency|35468|GBP}} as part of this contract.<ref name="bailii-contract-foi">{{cite web|title=FOI request regarding BAILII's contract with the Ministry of justice|url=https://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/73838/response/189463/attach/html/3/FOI%2070820%20Mark%20Goodge%20response%20290611.doc.html|publisher=What to they know}}</ref>
