[[Image:Südmähren Warte.JPG|thumb|Memorial near the former [[Znojmo|Znaim]] to the ''[[Sudetenland|Sudeten]]'' expellees of [[South Moravian Region|South]] Moravia (Kreis Znaim). The text translates as "Homeland rights are human rights."]] The '''right to homeland''' is according to some legal scholars a universal [[human right]], which is derived from the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]], including its Article 9.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Alfred-Maurice |last=de Zayas |title=International Law and Mass Population Transfers |journal=Harvard International Law Journal |year=1975 |pages=207–258}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |first=Alfred-Maurice |last=de Zayas |title=The Right to One's Homeland, Ethnic Cleansing and the International Criminal Tribunal for the Former Yugoslavia |journal=Criminal Law Journal |year=1996}}</ref> The concept evolved in German jurisprudence and is recognized in German constitutional law to a certain degree. Notable proponents of the concept include legal scholars [[Kurl Rabl]], [[Rudolf Laun]], [[Otto Kimminich]], [[Dieter Blumenwitz]], [[Felix Ermacora]] and [[Alfred-Maurice de Zayas]]. The concept is relevant to debates concerning [[ethnic cleansing]] in Europe after [[World War II]] (notably of Germans and Hungarians), ethnic cleansing in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], [[Cyprus]] and other areas.
